## ðŸ”„ 1. Input and Output Redirection in Linux

### ðŸ”¢ File Descriptors

| Type             | Name             | File Descriptor |
|------------------|------------------|------------------|
| Standard Input   | `stdin`          | `0`              |
| Standard Output  | `stdout`         | `1`              |
| Standard Error   | `stderr`         | `2`              |

> ðŸ“Œ **In Linux, everything is a file** â€“ regular files, directories, devices, etc.

---

### ðŸ“¥ Redirecting Standard Output

```bash
# Redirect output of a command to a file
ls -l > listings

# View the file contents
cat listings
ðŸ§  A single > will overwrite the file.
Use >> to append data to an existing file.

bash
Copy
Edit
ls -la >> listings
ðŸ“¤ Redirecting Standard Input
Feed a file as input to a command:

bash
Copy
Edit
cat < listings
Or use redirection in programs like mail:

bash
Copy
Edit
mail -s "Office Memo" user@abc.com < memo.txt
ðŸš« Redirecting Standard Error
bash
Copy
Edit
# Redirect only the error output to a file
ls -l /root 2> errorfile

# View the error message
cat errorfile
bash
Copy
Edit
# Another example with telnet
telnet localhost 2> errorfile
ðŸª 2. tee Command - View & Save Output Simultaneously
ðŸ› ï¸ Use Case
The tee command splits output:
âœ… shows it on the terminal
âœ… saves it to a file

bash
Copy
Edit
